---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About – Maksym Voitko" description="From civil engineering to leading AI teams. Maksym Voitko on building systems that survive production, shaping teams that multiply talent, and the messy middle where engineering meets reality." activeNav="about">
  <div class="about-page">
    <article class="prose" aria-label="About Maksym Voitko">
      <h1 class="page-title">About <span class="highlight">Me</span></h1>

      <p>
        Most people who lead AI teams started in computer science. I started by designing bridges. My first master's degree is in civil engineering, and that background gave me something I still rely on every day – a systems-thinking instinct for how complex structures hold together under pressure.
      </p>

      <p>
        The pivot happened when I realised software could be built the same way – layer by layer, with strong foundations and clear tolerances. I earned a second master's in computer engineering from KPI, began in QA, moved into test automation, and discovered that the obsession with reliability would become the thread connecting every role that followed.
      </p>

      <p>
        At <strong>glomex</strong> in Kyiv I shifted into data engineering – real-time analytics pipelines and billing systems on AWS. At <strong>SoftConstruct</strong> I led a sports AI team that stitched two 4K camera feeds into a panoramic view and used computer vision to track players and ball movement in real time. That project taught me what it takes to ship AI under real constraints – latency budgets, hardware limits, and zero tolerance for downtime.
      </p>

      <p>
        At <strong>GR8 Tech</strong> I designed an ML recommendation platform, built MLOps infrastructure from scratch with Kubernetes and Kubeflow, and created a YAML-driven DAG factory that let data scientists ship pipelines without writing code. As <strong>Head of Data &amp; AI at Honeycomb Software</strong>, I lead a team of ~15 engineers building production RAG systems, vectorisation pipelines, and enterprise AI products. Improved CV inference performance by ~40% through practical engineering – not exotic research, just smarter constraints.
      </p>

      <p>
        In April 2026 I'm joining <a href="https://monday.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Monday.com</a> as R&amp;D Tech Lead. Not because I wanted a bigger logo – because I wanted an environment where breadth across AI, data, platform, and leadership compounds harder. The interesting problems live at the seams between domains. I want to be where those seams are thicker.
      </p>

      <h2>What I <span class="highlight">believe</span></h2>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>RAG is not a product</strong> – it is a system full of failure modes. The hard part starts after the demo works.</li>
        <li><strong>MLOps should follow delivery reality</strong> – not tool fashion. Sequencing, team maturity, and budget matter more than the stack.</li>
        <li><strong>Performance is won through practical engineering</strong> – smarter data structures and surgical changes beat academic elegance when systems must ship.</li>
        <li><strong>The best engineering leaders are more technical, not less</strong> – breadth across data, platform, AI, and business is a force multiplier.</li>
        <li><strong>Architecture should compound</strong> – future-proof where it matters, keep everything else brutally simple.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What I <span class="highlight">talk about</span></h2>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Production RAG &amp; multi-agent systems</strong> – architecture, evaluation, and the gap between demo and deployment</li>
        <li><strong>MLOps under constraints</strong> – building infrastructure that survives budget, team maturity, and compliance pressure</li>
        <li><strong>Secure enterprise AI</strong> – private VPC, zero-egress deployment, AI governance for regulated industries</li>
        <li><strong>Engineering leadership</strong> – growing teams, designing interview loops, creating a culture of ownership</li>
        <li><strong>The non-traditional path</strong> – from civil engineering to AI leadership, and what systems thinking teaches you about both</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Beyond <span class="highlight">engineering</span></h2>

      <p>
        I'm a <strong>Lens Champion</strong> in the Kubernetes ecosystem, an angel investor at <a href="https://badideas.fund" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">BADideas.fund</a> backing early-stage CEE/CIS startups, and a member of the <strong>AI Accelerator Institute</strong>. I run a Ukrainian-language Telegram channel called <a href="https://t.me/forgottendatashadows" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Тіні Забутих Даних</a> where I write about AI and data engineering with less polish and more honesty than LinkedIn allows.
      </p>

      <p>
        When I'm not building systems, you'll find me reading sci-fi, playing basketball, or explaining to my daughter why the computer is thinking again.
      </p>

      <p class="about-cta">
        Want me to speak at your event? <a href="/speaking/">Let's talk &rarr;</a>
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .about-page {
    padding-top: calc(64px + 4rem);
    padding-bottom: 4rem;
  }

  .prose {
    max-width: 900px;
    width: 100%;
  }
  .prose h1 {
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }
  .prose p {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: var(--text);
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }
  .prose a {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 0.2em;
    transition: text-decoration-thickness 0.2s;
  }
  .prose a:hover { text-decoration-thickness: 2px; }
  .prose h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: clamp(1.3rem, 3vw, 1.6rem);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .prose ul {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }
  .prose li {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: var(--text);
    line-height: 1.8;
    padding: 0.3rem 0;
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    position: relative;
  }
  .prose li::before {
    content: '>';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
  }
  .prose li strong { color: var(--text); }
  .about-cta {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  .about-cta a {
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .about-page { padding: 64px 0 2rem; min-height: auto; }
  }
</style>
